{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17640131","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17640131"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:12:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:12:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17806"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17806","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17806"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10520"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72434"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10520","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10520"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17806"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57904"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"10197"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24551"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24554"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72434","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72434"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents with complete loss of her right thumbnail following a crush injury three months ago. The nail is now beginning to regrow from the posterior nail fold.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary site of nail plate formation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lunula","Nail fold","Nail bed","Hyponychium","Nail matrix"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Enail matrix\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary site of nail formation. It contains rapidly dividing epithelial cells that undergo keratinisation to form the nail plate. The matrix extends from beneath the proximal nail fold to the white, crescent-shaped \u003Cstrong\u003Elunula\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Enail bed\u003C/strong\u003E provides vascular tissue beneath the nail plate that supplies nutrients but does not produce the nail plate.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ehyponychium\u003C/strong\u003E forms a seal between the nail plate and fingertip beneath the free edge of the nail.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Enail fold\u003C/strong\u003E consists of skin that frames and protects the lateral and proximal nail margins.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe nail grows continuously throughout life, with complete replacement of the fingernail occurring every four to six months. This growth is entirely dependent on the proliferative activity of the nail matrix.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The nail plate is composed primarily of keratin proteins arranged in a hard, protective structure.","The nail matrix produces the nail plate through continuous cell division and keratinisation.","The nail bed provides blood supply and nutrients to support nail growth and attachment."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57904"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17806"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data"